    },
    {
      "id": "9Sknr50HL_i7iBjEyFCpa",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1491.5866619524998,
      "y": 1245.3609836135186,
      "width": 967.9193725585938,
      "height": 625,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bDz",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1401917344,
      "version": 1540,
      "versionNonce": 1970344864,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771767190465,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "HIGH LVL DESIGN: (happy path)\nget events\n0. event creator makes a request to the event CRUD services => for the normal ops for events\n    and these events will be stored on our DB which is the core entities we describe from before\n    (roughly write out the info talking about foreign keys between event, venue, performer, tickets)\n1. mention u will be using POSTgresql coz of ACID properties, SQL access patterns\n2. the READ op in this CRUD service will let us to get events\n\nsearch service\n3. search service is used to help us filter events using a special term\n4. for now the search service is very simple where its using a SQL search term\nselect * \nfrom DB\nwhere type in []\nand name like '%term%'\n5. this is really inefficient, and we will come back to optimize this\n\nbooking service\n* 2 step booking flow, reserve then confirm\n6. add new booking service\n7. for reserve, lookup row in DB & update our DB in the status column to reserve\n8. next request that comes in confirm(ticketId, paymentDetails)\n9. have stripe an API that u call, which has async call (POST to stripe)\n10. if successful payment, we will reach back out to set the status to booked\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "HIGH LVL DESIGN: (happy path)\nget events\n0. event creator makes a request to the event CRUD services => for the normal ops for events\n    and these events will be stored on our DB which is the core entities we describe from before\n    (roughly write out the info talking about foreign keys between event, venue, performer, tickets)\n1. mention u will be using POSTgresql coz of ACID properties, SQL access patterns\n2. the READ op in this CRUD service will let us to get events\n\nsearch service\n3. search service is used to help us filter events using a special term\n4. for now the search service is very simple where its using a SQL search term\nselect * \nfrom DB\nwhere type in []\nand name like '%term%'\n5. this is really inefficient, and we will come back to optimize this\n\nbooking service\n* 2 step booking flow, reserve then confirm\n6. add new booking service\n7. for reserve, lookup row in DB & update our DB in the status column to reserve\n8. next request that comes in confirm(ticketId, paymentDetails)\n9. have stripe an API that u call, which has async call (POST to stripe)\n10. if successful payment, we will reach back out to set the status to booked\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "TkszEXwpALSBy7eiZjaIa",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1439.390316757917,
      "y": 1921.513026303239,
      "width": 955.4595336914062,
      "height": 925,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bE0",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 60140128,
      "version": 1605,
      "versionNonce": 391613344,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771768911774,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "qns1. what happens if the person did not pay by the expiry time? status left reserved forever!\n\nsoln1:\n- add additional col with reservedTimestamp\n- when searching for the tickets, check for initial query AND reservedTimestamp + 10 < curr_time\n- query more complicated\n\n* query slower\n* coupling of status & reserved timestamp\n\nsoln2:\n- add cron job\n- query DB for every ticket & checking its reservedTimestamp & if more than 10 mins ago,\n    we delete the row\n\n* there is a delta in time here => cron job ran 10 mins ago, but reservedTimestamp is already over\n    now other ppl need to wait until this is done\n\nsoln3:\ndistribued lock\n- use ticketLock redis (or any other in MEM cache)\n- when ticket is reserved, keep track of this in redis\n- set ticketd: true, TTL 10\n- dont write to DB at all!!\n\n* why in mem distributed lock?\n=> we're gonna have multiple instances of booking services\n=> coz of horizontally scaling\n=> all need the same consistent view of the locked ticketId\n\nwhat if redis goes down?\n1. immediately bring redis back up\n2. but will have ppl who just lost their reservations\n3. whoever ends up submitting the purchase first will win\n\n* from here we need to talk to our product team\n* its an unlikely event => & if not then we havae to choose soln 1 or 2",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "qns1. what happens if the person did not pay by the expiry time? status left reserved forever!\n\nsoln1:\n- add additional col with reservedTimestamp\n- when searching for the tickets, check for initial query AND reservedTimestamp + 10 < curr_time\n- query more complicated\n\n* query slower\n* coupling of status & reserved timestamp\n\nsoln2:\n- add cron job\n- query DB for every ticket & checking its reservedTimestamp & if more than 10 mins ago,\n    we delete the row\n\n* there is a delta in time here => cron job ran 10 mins ago, but reservedTimestamp is already over\n    now other ppl need to wait until this is done\n\nsoln3:\ndistribued lock\n- use ticketLock redis (or any other in MEM cache)\n- when ticket is reserved, keep track of this in redis\n- set ticketd: true, TTL 10\n- dont write to DB at all!!\n\n* why in mem distributed lock?\n=> we're gonna have multiple instances of booking services\n=> coz of horizontally scaling\n=> all need the same consistent view of the locked ticketId\n\nwhat if redis goes down?\n1. immediately bring redis back up\n2. but will have ppl who just lost their reservations\n3. whoever ends up submitting the purchase first will win\n\n* from here we need to talk to our product team\n* its an unlikely event => & if not then we havae to choose soln 1 or 2",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
