      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771771841468,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep dive 1 : low latency search => coz of full table scan\nDeep dive 2 : handling popular events => in real tim\nDeep dive 3 : general scaling",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep dive 1 : low latency search => coz of full table scan\nDeep dive 2 : handling popular events => in real tim\nDeep dive 3 : general scaling",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "7mNOgOjYD7bceKQTzGdRY",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2613.291360597692,
      "y": 1425.6364665044728,
      "width": 1554.6387939453125,
      "height": 1125,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bE8",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1065574304,
      "version": 2528,
      "versionNonce": 498925152,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771774754609,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep dive 1 : low latency search => coz of full table scan\n1. use search optimized DB\n* Elastic search\n2. builds an inverted index => searching by term fast\n\nplayoff: [event1, event2, event3]\nswift: [event5, event6, event7]\n* instead of storing the event to \"entire string\", break the string down & store the events\n*elastic search also supports geo-spatial queries\n\n\nmaintaining consistency between elastic search & postgres\nhow do we get data into elastic search?\nhow do we make sure that data is consistent with our DB\n* not best practice to use elastic search as our true source of data\n    => durability concern\n    => no support for complex transaction (no real FK, joins)\n    => operational overhead -> bigger storage\n1. can use CRUD service to make changes for DB to also make change toelastic search\n    - its ok\n    - but need to handle complex logic on the app\n    - i.e. if either of them fail to write, need to undo (basically ensuring both have been updated)\n* becoz of logic, now we need to maintain consistency between the both. in the case 1 fails, then means the entire\nservice goes down coz of the inconsistency?\n* also increased number of writes from the actual server serving clients\n*whereas we could actually tolerate some search in accuracies, yet we want to ensure latency with clients are fast\n\n\n2. change data capture\n    - changes to main data store can be put on the stream\n    - and the change in events can be consumed\n* it has a limit for writes\n* for alot of writes/ change to the events, performers etc. this will hit a limit\n* events hardly change alot, plus their hardly ever added\n\nflow of data:\napp -> DB -> DB's WAL -> CDC reads WAL -> CDC publishes event to kafka -> indexer consumes -> indexer updates ES docs (JSON) & submit to elastic search\n\n* CDC - captures changes changes from DB & publishes to kafka (event emitter)\n* indexer - receives change (by consuming using a kafka consumer) transforms to ES doc, calls elastic search's index API, then upsert to it\n\nwhat about popular queries?\ncaching (cache tier OR CDN between client & LB)\n- great for returning the same query that people have\n- but is bad when we have too many queries with different terms that are no the exact same",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep dive 1 : low latency search => coz of full table scan\n1. use search optimized DB\n* Elastic search\n2. builds an inverted index => searching by term fast\n\nplayoff: [event1, event2, event3]\nswift: [event5, event6, event7]\n* instead of storing the event to \"entire string\", break the string down & store the events\n*elastic search also supports geo-spatial queries\n\n\nmaintaining consistency between elastic search & postgres\nhow do we get data into elastic search?\nhow do we make sure that data is consistent with our DB\n* not best practice to use elastic search as our true source of data\n    => durability concern\n    => no support for complex transaction (no real FK, joins)\n    => operational overhead -> bigger storage\n1. can use CRUD service to make changes for DB to also make change toelastic search\n    - its ok\n    - but need to handle complex logic on the app\n    - i.e. if either of them fail to write, need to undo (basically ensuring both have been updated)\n* becoz of logic, now we need to maintain consistency between the both. in the case 1 fails, then means the entire\nservice goes down coz of the inconsistency?\n* also increased number of writes from the actual server serving clients\n*whereas we could actually tolerate some search in accuracies, yet we want to ensure latency with clients are fast\n\n\n2. change data capture\n    - changes to main data store can be put on the stream\n    - and the change in events can be consumed\n* it has a limit for writes\n* for alot of writes/ change to the events, performers etc. this will hit a limit\n* events hardly change alot, plus their hardly ever added\n\nflow of data:\napp -> DB -> DB's WAL -> CDC reads WAL -> CDC publishes event to kafka -> indexer consumes -> indexer updates ES docs (JSON) & submit to elastic search\n\n* CDC - captures changes changes from DB & publishes to kafka (event emitter)\n* indexer - receives change (by consuming using a kafka consumer) transforms to ES doc, calls elastic search's index API, then upsert to it\n\nwhat about popular queries?\ncaching (cache tier OR CDN between client & LB)\n- great for returning the same query that people have\n- but is bad when we have too many queries with different terms that are no the exact same",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
